<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you have not seen The Crying Game, with which Channel 4 begins a new
season of 'Film Premiere', and if you still do not know about the twist in
the plot (I was taken entirely by surprise) it is worth watching. Not that
it is as good a movie as they thought in the US where it won the Oscar for
best screenplay. Americans confuse America's fight for independence with the
activities of Irish terrorists so that the IRA becomes a right-on
organisation on their side of the Atlantic. Still, this odd story of a black
soldier from the British Army who is held hostage by the IRA and asks one of
his captors to look after his lover back in London, does have an unusual
sense of style (10.00). The last episode in BBC2's likeable drama series
about mental patients, Takin' Over The Asylum (pity about that dropped 'g')
clashes with C4's superior culture series, Without Walls. Today this
includes an attack on television news values and what sounds like a
mick-take of 'The Late Show' (known here as 'The Night Show') where they are
trying to interview a chap called Shakespeare about one of his plays (9.00).
</TEXT>
