<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Milk price rises swiftly: First day of deregulation sees
some doorstep deliveries up 2p
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Deregulation of the milk market has already hit consumers with an increase
of 2p per pint in some doorstep deliveries yesterday and a similar rise
today in some supermarkets.
Tesco, the supermarket group, announced that a pint of fresh milk would go
up by 2p, or 7.7 per cent, to 28p because of the rise in the cost of raw
milk resulting from the new marketing arrangements which take effect today.
It said it would keep cheese price increases to 5 per cent in spite of a 20
per cent rise in wholesale milk prices to cheese makers. British cheddar
will rise shortly by 10p a pound to Pounds 2.05 and butter by about 8p a
pound in a few weeks' time.
Tesco blamed the increases on 'inflationary pressure' caused by the new
marketing system, which sees the abolition of the statutory Milk Marketing
Board and its replacement by a voluntary producers' co-operative, Milk
Marque.
The dairy trade, which plans to complain to the competition authorities in
London and Brussels, says Milk Marque, with 66 per cent of supplies in
England and Wales, is abusing its monopoly position by pushing up wholesale
prices sharply.
However, Mr William Waldegrave, agriculture minister, said yesterday there
was no justification for retail price increases of 2p or more on a pint of
milk as a result of deregulation.
'I suspect that some dairy companies have been preparing price rises which
are unrelated to the cost of milk and are seeking to blame these on the
changes,' he said.
Deregulation nevertheless continued to attract fierce criticism yesterday,
with the Safeway supermarket group saying the changes 'could be catastrophic
for some UK dairy product manufacturers', jeopardising jobs and leading to
more imported dairy products.
'Although we will continue to buy British where it is commercially sensible,
we fear continental producers will become more competitive on price in some
product areas', it warned. Safeway expects to raise prices by 2p to 3p a
pint.
The Labour party said the survival of the doorstep pint was under threat.
'The government's plans will be bad for ordinary families, as the price of
milk and dairy products goes up,' said Mr Gavin Strang, agriculture
spokesman.
Unigate, which delivers to 1.6m households in south and south-west England,
raised its prices yesterday by 2p a pint to 40p. It said this covered higher
wages and packaging costs and two previous raw milk price rises, as well as
higher costs associated with deregulation, which had triggered the overall
increase.
The government argues the new system will lead to a shake-out of excess
capacity devoted to low-value commodity products such as butter and skimmed
milk powder. This will create a more efficient industry and benefit
consumers in the longer run by reducing Britain's reliance on high
value-added dairy imports, it says.
</TEXT>
