<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Banks seek to counter EU rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading City investment banks fear a European Union directive aimed at
cushioning securities firms against shocks in the financial system will
force them to hold more capital than competitors in other countries.
They are asking the Treasury to interpret the Capital Adequacy Directive,
which takes effect in January 1996, in a manner which will allow some firms
to hold less capital than that required by Brussels.
Mr Kit Farrow, director-general of the London Investment Banking
Association, whose members are the City's biggest firms, said: 'These issues
are particularly acute for London, given the nature of the business here.
'It is in the UK where the trading activity is more developed. Even
Continental banks tend to run their trading books out of London. It may not
be very difficult for them to book the business elsewhere rather than in
London.'
London firms have been particularly critical of the directive, which they
say reflects a political compromise between member states where securities
industries vary greatly. It is understood to have been heavily influenced by
German universal banks, which typically have much more capital than is
required by regulators and which do not take large trading positions.
The directive says the 'trading book' of an investment bank should be
separated from the 'banking book', with a more liberal regime applying to
the former. Current UK rules do not make such a distinction and view the
risk activities of investment banks in their entirety.
In particular, the association is concerned about the directive's rules
which, unlike those applied by UK securities regulators, do not lower the
capital requirements for firms with diversified portfolios. Also, the
directive does not reduce capital requirements for holding securities which
offset each other's risks.
The association today will receive a boost from publication of the Bank of
England's quarterly report, which is highly critical of the directive. The
article, by Professor Richard Dale of Southampton University, does not
represent the view of the Bank.
Yet The Bank will release its own interpretation of how the directive will
apply to the securities activities of banks later this month.
Prof Dale says: 'The idea of segregating one part of a bank's business - its
securities trading operations - and applying separate and distinct
definitions of capital and capital adequacy to the different parts, appears
to make little prudential sense.'
He says the directive encourages banks to use their deposit base to
subsidise their riskier securities activities, giving the securities
activities of universal banks an advantage over non-bank securities firms.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
<XX>
