<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Companies plan policy shift over directors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY, Accountancy Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Listed companies plan to make more use of non-executive directors and
already increasingly use them in important meetings and on powerful
committees, according to a survey published yesterday.
Nearly 600 big companies were asked by Pro Ned, the employment agency for
non-executives, and the Board for Chartered Accountants in Business, about
their attitudes to non-executives and the work they do.
The survey concluded: 'Britain's major listed companies are leading a trend
towards a more professional and hard-nosed approach to the selection and use
of non-executive directors.' More than 80 per cent of the companies said
they expected non-executives to be more active and spend more time
understanding the company's business in the future.
There are still some indications that the old system lives on, however.
About 60 per cent of chairman admit their last non-executive appointment was
made through personal connections.
In contrast more than 40 per cent expect that their approach will change
with their next appointment and that the search for non-executives is now
more rigorous.
