<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Workers at Rover accept 10.7%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Rover Group car workers have voted narrowly to accept a pay deal which for
most of them is worth 10.7 per cent over the next two years.
In a postal ballot 11,993 backed the package - seen by many outside the
company as over-generous and a dangerous pointer for pay deals elsewhere -
and 11,102 voted against it.
Mr Tony Woodley, the TGWU national officer for the car industry, said: 'The
closeness of the result reflects the complexity of the deal and the
frustration among the workforce still undergoing major changes. The company
should take nothing for granted.'
Rover said it welcomed the result.
Mr Alistair Hatchett of Incomes Data Services, the independent pay analyst,
said: 'The narrow result reflects the fact that people are looking for a
little bit more on top of proposed pay offers.'
Although the deal provides a 3.7 per cent general pay increase from next
month and a further 4 per cent in November 1995 or inflation if higher, most
Rover workers will gain extra pay as a result of changes in the grading
structure that replaces five manual grades and six non-manual grades with
three joint grades. The unions have calculated that this will produce
increases of about Pounds 5 a week in the first year and a further Pounds
1.86 a week in the second.
Mr Hatchett said the recent rejection by Jaguar workers of a pay offer worth
7.5 per cent over two years may have hardened resistance among Rover Group
workers. A strike ballot is being held among Jaguar workers, although talks
are continuing between the company and the unions and neither side believes
they are on course to conflict.
Shopfloor unease reflected at the two companies seems likely to add to
pressures at Nissan and Peugeot-Talbot, which are about to negotiate deals.
</TEXT>
