<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Manager denies multiple share bid
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The contracts manager for City-based Gartmore Investment Management
repeatedly breached signed declarations designed to prevent multiple
applications in the power industry privatisation, a court was told
yesterday.
Mr Richard McGregor-Johnson, prosecuting, told Southwark Crown Court in
London that Mr Stuart Fisher used the names of colleagues to obtain hundreds
of shares he was not entitled to.
He said that Mr Fisher's allegedly dishonest dealings involved the 1991
privatisations of the English and Scottish electricity generating companies.
Mr McGregor-Johnson said: 'The prosecution say that this defendant was not
content to apply only once for his own benefit, but dishonestly made
multiple applications for shares in those two flotations.'
The prosecution alleges that Mr Fisher knew he was breaking the law.
Mr McGregor-Johnson said Mr Fisher, of Borough Green, Sevenoaks, Kent, had
denied four counts of obtaining property by deception and three of
attempting to obtain property by deception. He told the court that each
charge represented applications for 300 shares made either in the names of
people he worked with or knew.
He said: 'The crown says the defendant persuaded them to allow him to use
their names and put them forward for those applications on the basis that if
he was successful, they would get a few beers or a curry as a reward but he
would get any profits he made for the shares.'
Mr McGregor-Johnson said that all the applications were supported by cheques
drawn on Mr Fisher's account, although not all were successful. Mr Fisher
sold the shares he obtained through his company's dealing department.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
