<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Heath wants part of cash probe in public
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Edward Heath, the former Conservative prime minister, last night raised
the pressure on the Commons committee of privileges to hold at least part of
its inquiry into the 'cash for questions' affair in public.
He said that the departure from precedent this would involve was necessary
in order to redress the slump in public confidence in the Commons. Sir
Edward told the Commons that the presence of Sir Nicholas Lyell, the
attorney-general, as a member of the committee should ensure that witnesses
were not unfairly treated.
He declined to go as far as Mr Tony Benn, Labour MP for Chesterfield, who
wanted the views expressed by committee members as they debated their
conclusions to be heard in public. Mr Benn made clear that while he remained
a member of the committee he would provide his own report on all its
proceedings.
Mr John Prescott, Labour deputy leader, called on MPs to accept it was in
their interest that 'malpractice is rooted out and guidelines devised which
are easily understood by both us and the public'.
Mr Tony Newton, the leader of the Commons, said that all the evidence heard
by the committee would be published, along with its conclusions, and then
debated by the Commons.
Commenting on the possibility of a 'half-way house' with some of the
committee's proceedings being conducted in public and others in private, Mr
Newton said: 'I do not see how such an arrangement could be made to work.'
A Labour motion urging the committee to examine witnesses in public, except
when reasons of natural justice dictated otherwise, was defeated by a
majority of 37 (301-264). A government amendment reaffirming the committee's
right to decide for itself whether to sit in public or private was carried
without a division.
</TEXT>
