<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Angola rivals initial accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUSAKA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Angolan government and Unita rebels initialled a peace accord yesterday
to end almost two decades of civil war. The agreement caps a year of
UN-sponsored negotiations in the Zambian capital aimed at ending a conflict
that has caused hundreds of thousands of deaths and left millions homeless.
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and Mr Jonas Savimbi, Unita
leader, are expected to sign the accord in Lusaka later this month.
A peace agreement in 1991 led to elections the following year. They were won
by Mr dos Santos and his MPLA party, but Mr Savimbi rejected the results as
fraudulent. Fighting erupted again, continuing throughout the peace talks
and intensifying in recent weeks.
Under the accord, Unita fighters are to be demobilised eventually and either
sent home or incorporated into the national army. Unita will get some
government posts, specifically at provincial and municipal levels. A
commission representing the government, Unita and the UN will oversee
implementation of the accord.
</TEXT>
