<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Election called in Algeria peace bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ALGIERS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Algeria's military-backed government is to hold a presidential election by
the end of next year - in an apparent gesture to Moslem fundamentalists. The
decision, announced yesterday by President Liamine Zeroual, will cut short
his term of office by at least a year.
Algeria has been convulsed with conflict since parliamentary elections were
cancelled in January 1992, when the Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) appeared
on the verge of victory. In the ensuing turmoil, the FIS was banned and
thousands have been killed, including 68 foreigners targeted by Moslem
extremists.
The Algerian government recently opened contacts with militant Islamic
leaders, but President Zeroual said at the weekend there was an impasse
because they still supported insurgency. 'The moment has come to remove the
obstacles to people's expression and to allow them to speak directly,' he
declared yesterday. 'I have decided that the presidential elections will
take place before the end of 1995.'
Mr Zeroual stressed his 'determination' to pursue the 'eradication of
terrorism and violence'. His willingness to move towards elections appears
to be a gesture of conciliation to the more pragmatic fundamentalists, as
well as to Algeria's legal opposition parties. He said the elections would
be free but did not specify whether the FIS could run.
</TEXT>
