<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Solomons without a premier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONIARA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Solomon Islands was without a prime minister yesterday after Mr Francis
Billy Hilly resigned 18 days after refusing to step down when sacked by the
governor-general. 'I have decided it is finally time to allow for a change
in the leadership of the government,' Mr Hilly told parliament in the
capital, Honiara. It is unclear who will become the new prime minister. The
former prime minister (now opposition leader) Mr Solomon Mamaloni had been
sworn in as a caretaker premier on October 25. But it was unclear if Mr
Mamaloni's caretaker role remained valid following Mr Hilly's resignation.
Governor-General Moses Pitakaka was yet to make a statement on Mr Hilly's
resignation, and is now expected to call for nominations. Political analysts
say Mr Hilly's stance against alleged exploitation of tropical forests by
foreign logging companies had caused his loss of support. His resignation
ended almost three weeks of political crisis, which at times meant the
country had two prime ministers.
</TEXT>
