<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Bank says Italy may miss debt servicing target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Bank of Italy yesterday warned that continued high interest rates risked
pushing the cost of servicing the country's huge debt stock well beyond the
figure envisaged in the 1995 budget.
The warning, issued in the bank's quarterly economic bulletin, is the most
authoritative statement so far suggesting a fundamental element in the
budget calculations may be faulted.
It comes at a time when the right-wing coalition government and the
opposition are struggling to hammer out a parliamentary agreement on the
budget. The budget is seeking to find L50,000bn (Pounds 20bn) in fresh
revenues and, through spending cuts, to hold down the deficit to L138,000bn
 -equivalent to 8 per cent of GDP.
The report also confirms the strength of the recovery now taking place in
the Italian economy and claims inflationary pressures exist. However, the
bank says these should have been checked by the half percentage point rise
in the discount rate in mid-August.
It is this interest rate rise, interrupting a steady fall since late October
1992, that has undermined the budget calculations. The report points out
that short-dated government bonds are now 2.1 percentage points above the 8
per cent ceiling targeted for the year-end, and due to be sustained
throughout 1995. Similar considerations apply to medium-term treasury paper.
According to the bank, a one percentage point increase in interest rates
over the next 12 months implies an extra debt service cost of L6,000bn,
rising to an additional L14,000bn in the third year. The budget forecasts
debt service payments in 1995 at L176,250bn.
In the light of the recent tensions between the Bank of Italy and the
government, over the appointment of a new director-general at the bank, the
report uses even more cautious language than usual. However, between the
lines the bank is telling the government of Mr Silvio Berlusconi that the
budget may well have to be toughened.
'Only rigorous pursuit of the budget objectives - eventually toughened
because of exceeding the ceilings placed on interest payments - can reduce
the risks by altering the perceptions of the financial markets,' the report
comments.
The bank estimates that this year's inflation will be around 4 per cent
against the 3.5 per cent target, making the 2.5 per cent objective for 1995
harder to achieve. As domestic demand picks up, pushing GDP growth this year
to at least 2 per cent (against the 1.6 per cent expected), inflationary
pressures have begun to emerge. As a result, the bank has reaffirmed its
determination to keep a tight control of monetary policy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
