<HEADLINE>
FT  01 NOV 94 / Fayed steps up attack on Aitken: Hotel owner challenges
account of how Paris Ritz bill was paid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Jonathan Aitken's explanation of circumstances surrounding the payment of
his hotel bill at the Paris Ritz was challenged yesterday by Mr Mohamed
Fayed, the hotel's owner.
As Mr Fayed stepped up his allegations against Mr Aitken, Treasury chief
secretary, The Guardian was facing a Commons inquiry into its handling of
disclosures about the bill.
Miss Betty Boothroyd, the Speaker, ordered an investigation into The
Guardian's admission that it used a doctored Commons letterhead to seek
details of Mr Aitken's bill. Amid rowdy Commons exchanges, The Guardian's
use of subterfuge was described as 'quite deplorable' by Mr John Prescott,
Labour's deputy leader.
Sir James Spicer, a Tory member of the powerful privileges committee, said
Mr Peter Preston, The Guardian's editor, should resign. More than 100 Tory
backbenchers signed a Commons motion calling for Mr Preston's conduct to be
referred to Mrs Barbara Mills, the director of public prosecutions.
Mr Preston defended the use of the letterhead, which he said was part of an
arrangement with Mr Fayed intended to allow the Ritz management to release
details of the bill. 'Of course in retrospect, even for this internal
communication, it would have been better to have used another heading on the
notepaper. But the purpose was to protect the source at the time - it was
not to deceive anybody,' he said.
Mr Fayed, the owner of Harrods, said he took 'full responsibility' for
assisting The Guardian 'in the public interest'. But he raised further
questions about the way in which part of the bill was paid initially by Mr
Said Ayas, a former business associate of Mr Aitken.
He also claimed that inquiries in Paris had shown that a brunette woman who
paid part of the bill in cash had also paid bills for other guests with a
cheque drawn on Mr Ayas's bank account. The identity of the woman has been a
central aspect of the mystery surrounding the bill. Mr Aitken told an
inquiry carried out by Sir Robin Butler, cabinet secretary, that she was his
Swiss-born wife, Lolicia.
But Mr Fayed said the woman told the Ritz cashier in French: 'I have been
paying other bills at the George V and the Intercontinental. Here is the
cheque for Mr Ayas's account.'
He said that 'unless Mrs Aitken was also paying the other cheques to the
other hotels, the brunette in question was working on Mr Ayas's staff'.
Mr Fayed's spokesman, Mr Michael Cole, said there were inconsistencies
between the details of a cheque apparently written by Mr Aitken to clear up
a discrepancy over payment of his bill and the bank statement of the
recipient.
Pressure for a public hearing into cash for questions allegations against
two Conservative MPs increased as Sir Edward Heath, the former prime
minister, backed calls for the privileges committee to change its rules. Mr
David Alton, a Liberal Democrat member of the committee, said its inquiry
into Mr David Tredinnick and Mr Graham Riddick should be extended to include
other allegations of impropriety against ministers and MPs.
A Labour attempt to force the committee to sit in public was defeated by 301
votes to 264 in the Commons last night, leaving the committee to make its
own decision today. The seven Labour members decided last night to end a
boycott of the committee, suggesting they believe it will decide to sit at
least partly in public.
Bill 'discrepancies', Page 9
Joe Rogaly, Page 20
Observer, Page 21
</TEXT>
<XX>
