<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / Business Travel: Calls from the air
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
KLM, the Dutch airline, is installing telephones in every business-class
seat of its long-haul Boeing 747s, and on wall-mounted units in tourist
class.
The airline will use the Inmarsat satellite network.  This permits almost
unrestricted calls, as opposed to other carriers which use
aircraft-to-ground systems, where calls are possible only within range of a
ground station.  Calls will cost Dollars 9 a minute, with a connection fee
of Dollars 5.
