<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Verbal tics and visual trickery now dominate TV news bulletins, and Allison
Pearson aims a few kicks below the console desk in Without Walls (Tuesday,
9.00-9.30pm, C4) - a powerful polemic that takes the genre to task for being
'splendidly idiotic' in its mannerisms. She also accuses it of political
bias, parochialism, sexism and a tendency towards tabloidism. Thank God
Reginald Bosanquet, the famed ITV newscaster, isn't alive to see this.
Phillip Larkin was wrong: sex did not arrive in Britain between the trial of
Lady Chatterley and the Beatles' first LP. A new series, Forbidden Britain
(Thursday, 9.45-10.30pm, BBC2), examines what remained unspoken until
recently. It includes interviews with a woman who was considered a criminal
because she had sex before the age of consent. And memories of the second
world war as a time when Britons pulled together are belied by figures
showing that between 1939 and 1941, crime against children and young people
rose by half. Eye-opening stuff.
There could be a sense of deja vu in Harry Enfield and Chums (Friday,
9.30-10.00pm, BBC1). If you think you have seen many of the characters - you
have. His sidekick, Paul Whitehouse, has just finished his first comedy
series, which owes a debt to Enfield's comic personae. However, there are
plenty of new characters, including the Self-Righteous Brothers, who can
solve all problems from the comfort of a bar stool, and Brian Bewildered,
who can't tie a shoelace without getting confused over the ins and outs.
Watch for Merchant-Ivory's Terminator III.
There is a touch of opportunism in the casting of Juliet Aubrey as Isabella
in one of Shakespeare's most problematic plays, Measure For Measure
(Saturday, 9.30-11.20pm, BBC2). Having made Dorothea Brooke, the most
priggish heroine in English literature, seem sympathetic, Aubrey may well
prove a success as Shakespeare's morally riven nun, a part which has
defeated many a more experienced actress. The popularity of Aubrey's
performance in Middlemarch should help draw viewers.
</TEXT>
