<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / This Week: Music
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER ASPDEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The muses of two very different generations of rock music release new albums
this week: Joni Mitchell's Turbulent Indigo (Reprise) is characteristically
serious and moralistic, but always intelligent. Sadly, however, Mitchell
seems to have mislaid her sense of fun temporarily. An idea of her mood can
be gleaned from the cover, on which her face is transposed on to a Van Gogh
self-portrait. About a million miles from the sensibility of this
well-crafted album is Madonna's Bedtime Stories (Maverick/Sire), in which
our heroine goes soft and gooey after years of abrasively flaunting her
sexuality before us. Without wishing to sound like an old woman, it simply
doesn't work; most depressing of all is the lack of attention to the quality
of her songs, which actually used to be one of her strong points.
Christmas compilation fever is already beginning to break out in the shops.
It is hard to imagine that there is a new way of packaging Motown's peerless
collection of classics, but Motown - The Ultimate Hits Collection claims to
have remastered 46 tracks (41 of them Top Ten UK hits), from Mary Wells to
Boyz II Men, for our rediscovery. I'm afraid I still prefer the scratchy
singles. INXS - The Greatest Hits (Mercury) celebrates the band's 17 years
with a resume of their best-known material.
Russian spirituality seems to be going down a treat in the faithless west
these days. Latest releases in a growing genre are Rachmaninov's Vespers
(Philips), featuring Nikolai Korniev conducting the St Petersburg Chamber
Choir (they are midway through a European tour), and Night Vigil (Deutsche
Grammophon), a live recording of the Russian Orthodox Palm Sunday all-night
service from the Cathedral of the Transfiguration in St Petersburg. Staying
with that city, Sony Classical have released nine new recordings in their St
Petersburg Classics series, which is dedicated to rediscovering the music
and the artists of the former Soviet Union. Among the releases are
symphonies by Tchaikovsky and Rachmaninov, and Shostakovich's moving chamber
symphony In Memory of the Victims of Fascism and War.
Gavin Bryars, whose Jesus Blood Never Failed Me Yet was one of the unlikely
successes of last year, has based his latest work on one of the greatest
tragedies of the century. The Sinking of the Titanic (Point) takes as its
starting point the reported fact that the ship's band kept playing even as
she went down. Bryars's sombre piece is intensely uncomfortable to listen
to, but it is a remarkably bold and haunting experiment.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
