<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / FT Guide to the Future of Lloyd's
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyd's seems to be heading for radical change? How radical is it really?
By the 21st century, Lloyd's might in theory find itself transformed. Names
 -the individuals whose assets have historically been invested on the basis
of unlimited liability - may have switched to limited liability. Their
investments may even be subsumed in a few large companies, many listed on
stock exchanges, which might dominate the 300-year-old London insurance
market.
However, all this could prove to be a fantasy. In practice, changes are only
being made gradually. This is partly because the volume of corporate capital
in the market is growing slowly, accounting for only about 15 per cent of
funds at Lloyd's this year. Traditional Names remain the dominant voice and
are anxious to protect their interests.
But the slow pace of change is also because Lloyd's has yet to shake off
past problems. Losses between 1989 and 1991 totalled Pounds 7bn. Many
possible asbestosis and pollution liabilities outstanding on old policies,
some dating to the 1940s, have yet to be quantified. Lloyd's must settle its
debts as well as try and make plans for the future.
For these reasons, David Rowland, Lloyd's chairman, and Peter Middleton,
chief executive, have not attempted wholesale reform of Lloyd's. Their first
aim has been to restore profitability, and that has left many anomalies
untackled. For instance, the market still trades via syndicates which are
reformed each year. Normal insurance companies, which smooth losses and
profits over several years, regard such practices as bizarre and outdated.
Is change the result of Lloyd's troubles?
Yes. If the market had been making profits in the past few years - or even
modest losses - the impetus for reform would not have been as strong.
Lossmaking Names appear to be making progress in winning compensation in
court for past losses. Won't that stymie Lloyd's reforms?
Not directly. The disputes are between Names and the professional agencies
which handled their money, rather than Lloyd's central organisation.
Compensation will be paid out of the assets or insurance policies of those
agencies, some of which are in liquidation.
Inevitably, however, some of the bad feeling between Names and agents has
wider repercussions, and will deter future investors. Lloyd's also faces a
struggle in recouping money that should have come from Names but which it
has paid out of its central fund, which protects policy-holders.
Why should anyone want to invest again on the basis of 'unlimited
liability'?
Unlimited liability may seem a legal nonsense - after all, nobody has
unlimited assets. But the fact that in the past Names have been prepared to
risk all their assets meant that a higher level of gearing was possible.
Some of the wealthiest Names, for instance, are allowed by Lloyd's rules to
underwrite policies worth five times their investment. That increases the
risks, but also the returns. Corporate capital generally cannot arrange such
high gearing.
Moreover, many Names who are able to continue trading might be advised to
remain in the market. Lloyd's is expected to record profits in the 1993 and
probably 1994 underwriting years. Under Lloyd's accounting rules, those
profits should begin to flow into Names' bank accounts over the next few
years.
Who would want to invest via one of the new Lloyd's companies?
Lloyd's image has not been helped by its past losses and the continuing
publicity surrounding the Names' court battles. The market's structure is
also byzantine, making it cumbersome and difficult for investors to
understand.
But Lloyd's is currently making money and has considerable underwriting
expertise. That makes it attractive for some investors. The future success
of corporate capital will depend on the ingenuity of corporate financiers in
setting up vehicles which offer the prospect of decent returns - as well as
whether Rowland and Middleton succeed in streamlining Lloyd's organisation
and ensuring long-term profitability.
Will the cost of insurance premiums be affected by reform at Lloyd's?
Almost certainly not. In fact, the chain of causation might be the other way
around. Lloyd's fortunes may well be determined by its ability to ride out
the next downturn in a cyclical world insurance market. The danger is of
premium rates softening in the good times, leaving the market prone to
losses in future. That would not only speed the exit of the traditional Name
but deter many corporate investors.
</TEXT>
