<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / This Week: Australia, winning at any price - Sport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEITH WHEATLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sport is Australia's established church. Something has to be, in what is one
of the world's most enthusiastically secular nations, a place where
organised religion is seldom glimpsed. In Perth, England's cricketers are
currently playing Western Australia in the first major game of the Ashes
tour.
For England players such as Darren Gough and Joey Benjamin, debutantes Down
Under, their first hours in the vast amphitheatre of the West Australian
Cricket Association ground (or WACA, to rhyme with Packer) will be
unforgettable.
The pitch is as iron-hard as the spectators, let alone the Aussie
cricketers. Ten years ago I awoke, jet-lagged, on the first day of my first
visit to Australia in a hotel room adjoining the WACA. An England v
Australia Test match was in progress. It was a Saturday, so I found my way
to the main stand, on the fringe of a group of tough-looking characters each
with a two-litre jug of ice-cold Emu lager to hand. Their concentration on
every ball and every stroke was ferocious. At the tea interval I summoned
the courage to ask if they had come far to see the match.
They were iron-ore miners from the Pilbara, based at Port Hedland nearly
1,000 miles away, and had driven down through the night to see just one day
of the Test. Most had to be back at work the next morning. It was a
revelatory insight into the commitment - sometimes joyless but always
effective - that sport inspires across the Wide Brown Land.
A few days ago a friend in Sydney sent me a copy of The Bid, a
recently-published account of how Sydney won the battle to host the 2000
Olympic Games. Since the author of the book is Rod McGeoch, the corporate
lawyer who spent three years and ADollars 28m (Pounds 12.5m) as head of the
bidding team, it should be the inside story. Overall it reminds me in tone
and content of nothing so much as modern military history - the unglimpsed
staff-work behind victory in the Falklands or on the Normandy beaches, for
example.
McGeoch's team knew from Day 1 that their goal was to capture the votes of
94 members of the International Olympic Committee. Athens' loss to Atlanta
in 1990 had convinced them that underdogs could win. 'Sentimental favourites
and powerful candidates could be beaten using a well thought-out strategy
based on building personal relationships with the IOC members', writes
McGeoch, who, at the outset of the campaign, had never met anyone from the
IOC.
Sydney put a remarkable effort into getting this all-powerful electorate to
visit them. When the IOC held its 1991 annual conference in Birmingham,
McGeoch and his team were naturally prowling the lobbies, urging 'the
voters' to hop on a Qantas flight asap. Furthermore, they had an official of
the Australian Immigration Service, a department modelled on the Kremlin,
sitting in reception at the Hyatt Regency handing out instant visas.
Lobbies and lobbying loom large in The Bid. McGeoch and his charm offensive
were constantly present at major international sports conferences. 'We would
go to all the official functions', he writes. 'But a large part of what we
did was actually wait around hotel lobbies where members were either staying
or attending meetings to catch them for a chat. . . I'd insist we had a
roster of people to wait around the lobbies. When our wives travelled with
us they too would be rostered. We used to call ourselves 'lobby lizards'.'
At the Albertville winter Olympics, New South Wales premier Nick Greiner
caught a little flak for slipping the lobby leash and going off skiing. At
the IOC session in Birmingham the Aussies would rise at dawn to ensure that
they got the largest, most prominent table at breakfast in the Hyatt, so
that members might join them for coffee and croissants if they wished.
A campaign rule rigidly precluded approaching any VIP who was already
eating. Government, both state and federal, figures largely in this account.
Manchester, which was bidding for the same Games, made much of the fact that
it had some Whitehall cash and occasionally got to see prime minister John
Major. Sydney's bid had politicians crawling all over it, and was
practically an arm of the state.
'I always had to remember that I was a public servant whose responsibility
it was to make sure that I did not embarrass my minister,' writes McGeoch.
Beijing was Sydney's great rival for the 2000 Olympics, and The Bid focuses
on the 'official' nature of China's campaign, with hundreds of government
officials scurrying around. Yet in some ways this 'quango' element was what
the two favourites had in common.
Manchester and Berlin, in comparison, were models of free enterprise
initiative. When the IOC members were actually in Sydney they were feted
beyond belief, not so much with lavish wining and dining - now against the
rules - but with little tricks that money couldn't buy.
One night at the Opera House an IOC member's wife became unavoidably delayed
in the ladies' toilet during the interval. Despite an increasingly restive
audience, the general manager was summoned and told that the show must not
go on. Not a note was sung until 'Mrs K' had resumed her seat.
England's cricketers are about to start a battle for the Ashes against a
team as formidably well prepared as Australia's Olympic campaign. In
business, Australians tend to cut corners. Culturally, they aim low. But in
sport they will pay any price and make any sacrifice to win.
</TEXT>
<XX>
