<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / Engineering warms to minimum wage
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Four out of 10 UK engineering companies support the introduction of a
statutory minimum wage, says a survey from the Engineering Employers
Federation.
Although just over half those polled opposed the idea, the level of support
among 100 engineering business leaders is surprisingly high.
A similar number believed a minimum wage would have no effect on
unemployment levels, while 51 per cent said the jobless total would rise.
More predictably, two-thirds of companies said that accepting the provisions
of the European Union's social chapter would lead to substantial job losses
in the UK.
The results are contained in the EEF Manufacturing Matters Survey, conducted
in the approach to today's Manufacturing Matters conference in London.
More than half of those polled said short-termism by the government had
con-tributed to the decline in British industry in the past decade.
Government attitudes were blamed by 58 per cent of companies in the survey,
a slightly higher proportion than those blaming short-termism among
management or in the City, or the 'roller-coaster economy' and high interest
rates.
Mr Graham Mackenzie, the EEF's director-general, said: 'This survey
reinforces concern among engineering businesses that a longer-term strategic
outlook is needed from government, industry and the City if UK manufacturing
is to be competitive.'
The poll was sponsored by Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountants, and Lloyds
Bank Commercial Service. Employers who recruit permanent staff from the
unemployed register should be exempt for a period from paying national
insurance contributions as a stimulus to help the long-term jobless back
into work, Robert Taylor writes.
This is the key proposal published today by the EEF in its response to the
white paper on competitiveness.
Mr Mackenzie said: 'I believe this kind of incentive would spur on the
movement of people back to work.'
The response is critical of the white paper. 'It does not provide the
strategic vision which the EEF had been hoping for,' it says.
</TEXT>
