<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / Major set for sleaze fightback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday offered strong backing for Mr Jonathan Aitken, the
Treasury chief secretary, as the government prepared for a Commons
confrontation over allegations of ministerial sleaze.
The prime minister's stance came amid strong attacks by Conservative MPs on
Mr Peter Preston, editor of The Guardian, following the disclosure that his
newspaper had used House of Commons notepaper to obtain a copy of Mr
Aitken's Pounds 1,000 bill for a stay at the Ritz Hotel in Paris last year.
Mr Preston said the note-paper, bearing Mr Aitken's name, had not been used
to deceive or mislead, but to protect the newspaper's source - Mr Mohamed
Fayed, the owner of Harrods and the Ritz.
But Sir James Spicer, a member of the powerful privileges committee, was
among a number of senior Conservative MPs condemning the action and
demanding an investigation by the Commons into the news-paper's action.
Mr Aitken - at the centre of a political row over the payment of his bill at
the Ritz - meanwhile dismissed suggestions that he had broken parliamentary
rules by not declaring a company directorship.
Friends of the Treasury minister said the company involved - Fadace Ltd -
was an inconsequential offshoot of another company, Al Bilah Co UK, which
had been declared by the minister in the register of MPs' interests. Mr
Aitken received no salary or fees from Fadace.
Mr Major's backing for Mr Aitken followed renewed demands from Labour for
the Commons to hold public rather than private hearings into allegations of
financial impropriety.
But Downing Street said Mr Major had not budged from his view that public
hearings would prompt unfounded smears against innocent MPs. Senior
Conservatives added that the government could not intervene in the work of
the all-party privileges committee without challenging its long-standing
tradition of independence.
Labour, whose MPs are boycotting the present investigations, has tabled a
motion for today's Commons debate demanding public hearings by the
privileges committee of charges against individual MPs. But a government
amendment says the committee itself must decide on its procedures.
In spite of today's expected confrontation senior Conservatives stressed
that there was still scope for a compromise between Labour and Tory MPs on
the committee. One suggestion was that individuals' evidence could be heard
in private while the committee held public sessions to debate wider points
of principle.
</TEXT>
