<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / Hambros explores rail stock interest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Hambros Bank, which has been appointed to market the three railway
rolling-stock leasing companies to be carved out of British Rail, this week
will start exploring Japanese interest in the sale.
Hambros executives, who last week visited the US, report strong initial
overseas enthusiasm. Industry analysts suggest that the three companies,
with combined annual revenues of Pounds 804m, could fetch between Pounds 2bn
and Pounds 4bn.
The companies will be expected to spend about 40 per cent of their turnover
on maintenance, but labour costs are low. Each employs about 50 people. The
companies, Eversholt Train Leasing, Poterbrook Leasing and Angel Train
Contracts, known together as the Roscos, own nearly all BR's passenger
trains.
In the next month Hambros will speak to all parties which it thinks could be
interested. It plans to issue a sales memorandum in the first quarter of
next year, to accept bids in early summer and to complete the sales by
autumn.
Hambros reports interest from UK venture capitalists, from US banks and
leasing companies, and from European organisations. No purchaser will be
allowed to own more than one Rosco, in order to create competition.
Mr Tony Mallin, vice-chairman of Hambros, said any purchaser would be well
placed to make further acquisitions in other countries.
