<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / Football ticket rules impose a penalty: The application
system for the European championship has amazed fans and Jacqueline Shorey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACQUELINE SHOREY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Tickets for the 1996 European football championship went on general sale
last Thursday. Application forms are available from any Midland Bank.
'Applying for Euro 96 tickets is so easy . . .' it said.
A friend and I wanted to see some group games and the final at Wembley.
To buy two final tickets I had to buy four for the semi-finals. The cheapest
option on current ticket availability for seeing games at Wembley - where
England's group will play - was to buy four Pounds 50 semi-final tickets,
two of which I did not want. Never mind, I thought. I will get rid of them.
However, the same rule applied for the quarter-finals - another four tickets
at Pounds 35. Another two spares.
The rules also said that I must buy tickets for three group matches in order
to qualify to buy tickets for the knock-out games (quarters, semis and the
final). Fair enough, I wanted to see some group games. However, the rules
said I could not buy more tickets for knock-out games than for group
matches.
Did I understand correctly? Did I really have to buy four tickets for each
of the three group matches?
I rang the helpline number. Yes, those were the rules. I had to buy 12
tickets at Pounds 25 each to qualify. That took the grand total - the
minimum I could spend - to Pounds 760, which included Pounds 320 for 10
tickets I did not want. I could have bought the best seats at Wembley and
spent Pounds 1,820, of which Pounds 780 would have been for 10 unwanted
tickets.
What to do with the spare tickets? The criminal justice bill will outlaw
touting and besides, the Football Association's conditions of sale say: 'A
ticket shall become void if it is passed on, with or without payment, to
another party without the prior consent of the FA.' I could not even give
them away.
Mr Steve Beauchampe, international officer of the Football Supporters'
Association, offered his opinion: 'Fans will fall into two categories, those
who sell the tickets on at face value - who wouldn't dream of ripping off
another supporter - and those who think: 'I've spent a lot of money up front
 -now's my chance to get a bit more back'.'
Mr Mike Parry of the FA said they expected the tournament to sell out and
had 'agonised' over the fairest possible ticket system. In order to give
priority to real fans tickets went on sale at the end of January to league
club season ticket holders and England Travel Club members who have already
bought 150,000 of the 1.3m tickets. In order to get tickets for the final,
they also had to buy tickets for earlier games, but had not been compelled
to buy 'spares' in order to qualify.
The 'progressive loyalty' system tried to ensure tickets for the later
stages of the competition went to real fans who had attended group games.
What about four fans, who had proved their loyalty by going to three group
matches, the quarters and semis. Their ticket purchases only qualify for two
final tickets. Did the FA have any advice on who should get the final
tickets? 'Toss a coin?' said Mr Parry.
Mr Beauchampe was not impressed. 'I was aghast when I read the ticket
application form,' he said. 'We accept that because of huge demand there
have to be restrictions on final tickets, and approved a scheme where people
had to go to group games to qualify. But to attend those games and then not
get a final ticket is unfair. The system betrays the loyalty of football
fans.'
What about fans from other countries in the competition? Unlike English fans
who are having to pay 20 months in advance, our European rivals will have
another year - until December 1995, when the draw is held. At least those
fans will know what they are buying - all the English fans can do now is
book a seat at a ground, even though fixtures have not been arranged.
Total ticket sales should generate about Pounds 60m. That money and the
interest it earns before June 1996 will go into a trust fund. After
expenses, profits will be split between the FA and Uefa, the European body,
and put back into the game.
Mr Parry denied that tickets had gone on sale too soon. The competition will
be twice the size of the Swedish championship in 1992, when tickets went on
sale 10 months in advance. 'This competition is twice as big and needs twice
the time,' he said.
Mr Rod Cornes of Synchro Systems, the Newcastle-under-Lyme software company
which is organising ticket sales on behalf of the FA, said 70 per cent of
those who had bought tickets were using direct debit and the average
expenditure was Pounds 500.
I told Mr Cornes about my surplus tickets and then had a brainwave. I'd read
in the small print that 'all tickets will be refundable up until 30 June
1995, subject to a Pounds 3 per ticket administration fee'. I would keep the
12 tickets I wanted and return my 10 spares for a refund. The administration
fee was annoying but I would offload the tickets legitimately and get my
cash back.
'We've thought of that,' Mr Cornes said. 'Our computer is very
sophisticated. If it sees that you're trying to return tickets that
qualified you for final tickets, it will invalidate your final tickets.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
