<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / Airlines hit at levy on departures
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The introduction tomorrow of an airport departure tax in Britain was
attacked yesterday by the International Air Transport Association as an
example of government taxation policies undermining the recovery of the
airline industry.
Mr Pierre Jeanniot, director-general of the trade organisation that
represents more than 200 international airlines, criticised the tax in his
annual report, prepared for the association's annual meeting in Mexico City
today.
Mr Jeanniot said that the Pounds 325m the UK levy would raise would go
directly to the Treasury. 'Taxes simply increase airline costs at a time
when consumers are demanding lower fares,' he said.
The association said the industry had lost Dollars 4.1bn (Pounds 2.6bn) on
international scheduled services alone last year and had losses for the past
four years totalling Dollars 15.6bn.
But things were improving, with traffic growing more quickly than capacity.
Mr Jeanniot said airlines were expected to show a modest profit on
international scheduled services of about Dollars 1bn this year. But he
warned that 'profitability of Dollars 1bn would represent less than 1 per
cent of turnover against a steady requirement for 5 to 6 per cent.'
The tax has been attacked by UK airlines, which say that it will distort
competition because it does not apply to other forms of transport.
It has caused problems for airlines because of confusion about the rate to
be charged for different European countries.
The tax involves a levy of Pounds 5 for travel to European destinations and
Pounds 10 to other international destinations. Airlines expected the Pounds
5 levy to apply only to European Union member states, however, and have been
charging Pounds 10 for travel after November 1 to European destinations
outside the EU.
But the tax for all European destinations has now been set at Pounds 5, and
airlines will be refunding passengers who have been overcharged when they
check-in.
A British Airways official said: 'This is causing us a big headache.'
Sir Colin Marshall, BA's chairman, has said that revenues from the new tax
should be ploughed back into improving UK aviation infrastructure.
The government has countered that the UK was one of the few remaining
countries which did not levy an airport departure tax.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
