<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / Israel eases currency curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SILVER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Israel yesterday announced a further step in liberalising its currency. From
tomorrow Israelis going abroad on holiday will be free to take up to Dollars
7,000 in cash, instead of the present ceiling of Dollars 3,000. They will
also have unrestricted use of credit cards for buying goods and services,
though not for drawing cash. Previously, any credit card transactions were
subject to the Dollars 3,000 limit. A Bank of Israel spokesman acknowledged
that the change was mainly psychological. The average Israeli tourist drew
only Dollars 1,500 when travelling. But it would affect the climate and
enhance the sense of a free currency. Business travellers already enjoy a
ceiling of Dollars 9,000, which can be increased where justified.
</TEXT>
