<HEADLINE>
FT  31 OCT 94 / 'Foul' cried over football tournament ticket system
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JACQUELINE SHOREY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Football Association was accused yesterday of encouraging a black market
in tickets for the 1996 European football championship, by unfairly
requiring fans to buy tickets they do not want. The tournament is to be
hosted by England.
Mr Chris Smith, shadow heritage secretary responsible for sport, said: 'The
aim of ensuring that the real fans get the best chance for tickets is a
sensible one, but the Football Association appears to have devised a system
which, perhaps inadvertently, will not end up with this aim fulfilled.
Furthermore, it will facilitate the starting up of an illegal black market.'
FA rules mean that a fan wanting one Pounds 60 ticket for the Wembley final
must spend at least Pounds 280 on a total of 11 tickets. For one final
ticket, fans must buy two for the semi-finals, two for the quarters, and two
for each of three group games - even if they want only one for each.
The tickets went on general sale last Thursday on a 'progressive loyalty'
basis:
To buy tickets for the final knock-out stages of the competition - the
quarter-, semi- and final matches - fans must buy tickets for at least three
matches from the earlier group stage.
To qualify to buy one ticket for the final, fans must buy two for the semis.
To qualify to buy semi-final tickets, supporters must buy two for the
quarter-finals. However, they cannot buy more tickets for the knock-out
matches than for the group games, so they must buy two tickets for each of
the three group games - even if they want only one.
Supporters say the unwanted tickets will deprive other fans of the chance to
see games and encourage fans to become ticket touts. 'Without question, this
system will create a black market,' said Mr Steve Beauchampe, international
officer of the Football Supporters' Association.
Mr Mike Parry of the FA said he hoped that love of the game would compel
holders of spare tickets to pass them on to true fans.
Imposing a penalty, Page 7
</TEXT>
