<DOCNO>FT944-12903</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EJ3AVAFQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941029
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 94 / FT Schools 1000 - Survey of Secondary Education (7): Calling
at half-way houses - The appeal of informality
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If pupils want to escape school at 16, but want a 'halfway house' before
going to university, sixth-form colleges may be the answer.
More than 100 have been set up in the past two decades by local authorities
mostly trying to save money  - they can be more economical than maintaining
small sixth forms at schools.
The government is showing signs of halting this, with the Department for
Education giving the go-ahead for several 11-16 schools to start sixth
forms. Former education secretary, John Patten, had said they were like 'a
body without a head'. All sixth-form colleges have been removed from local
authority control, and are funded on the same basis as further education
colleges.
But the colleges, at least in some cases, are beginning to show their worth.
Judging them for league table purposes is difficult because their large size
 - one of their prime advantages as it allows them to provide a broader,
more flexible curriculum  - makes it harder for them to sustain a high
average points score.
Most are non-selective and cater for students doing mainly vocational
courses. It is common for students to take a vocational course plus an
A-level in maths, which would show up badly in the FT rankings.
Some further education colleges offer no A-levels, or only offer them as
access courses for adults, which should not be compared with teaching
18-year-olds. Others offer full-time A-level courses as an addition to
vocational training, but these are not included, as it would be unfair to
take A-level results as a measure of overall performance.
The Department for Education's league tables tackle these problems by
quoting the average UCAS points for candidates who attempt two or more
A-levels, and for those who attempt fewer than two. This separates those
taking an A-level to top up a vocational course from students taking a fully
academic course.
The sixth-form colleges in the FT's table (above) are all primarily
academic, and their results cover all pupils who attempted A-levels. Once it
is taken into account that they are offering broad curricula and entering as
many as 700 candidates each year, some of their results seem spectacular.
As usual, catchment areas are the prime determinant of success, with
Cambridge's Hills Road Sixth Form College topping the rankings.
Colchester Sixth Form College is perhaps the most dramatic example of the
benefits of large scale. Entering around 700 candidates each year, it takes
students regularly from nine schools, and attracts many more from outside
its catchment.
It offers 40 A-level subjects including law, physical education, and
philosophy. Students are also offered 19 subjects at AS-level, allowing them
more opportunities to achieve a balance between arts and sciences than with
conventional A-levels.
The college also regularly manages to find places at Oxford and Cambridge
for about 15 students each year. Its top 100 candidates this year gained an
average of 33.07 UCAS points, which ranks the college among academic giants
like Westminster and St Paul's.
This was achieved despite the presence in Colchester of two of the country's
most successful grammar schools, which both take 100 pupils each year.
Although the college is over-subscribed, many students have failed a grammar
school entrance exam.
Principal John Edwards says that some parents are worried by the informality
 - there is no uniform, and staff are addressed by their first names.
Internal politics also resembles a university union, with elected student
representatives having a voice in college policies. During breaks the
college, based around old school buildings in the centre of Colchester,
feels more like a university than a school.
Its size helps in other respects. Colchester finished third in the national
swimming championships  - behind Millfield and Kelly, both of which
specialise in the sport.
The advantages of scale are great, and league tables often fail to reflect
them. The UK's largest comprehensive - the Stantonbury Campus in Milton
Keynes  - also resembles a university more than a school, with fine theatre
and sporting facilities available to the community. Its aggregate results
may look less impressive but still include examples of excellence.
Elsewhere, urban schools have countered threats to their sixth forms by
starting sixth-form consortia and by pooling resources, allowing students to
take an A-level at another school if there is insufficient demand for it at
their own.
One outlandishly named example in the FT-1,000 is La SWAP in north-west
London. This is a joint operation of La Sainte Union, William Ellis, Acland
Burghley, and Parliament Hill schools in Camden, London. Its position,
barely below average for the FT-1000, in an area where it competes against
some of the most selective academic schools, is also better than it appears.
