<HEADLINE>
FT  29 OCT 94 / FT Schools 1000 - Survey of Secondary Education (3):
Scotland ready to rule - Why the Scottish system is increasingly envied
south of the border
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Alumni of Scottish independent schools may soon be running the country.
Prince Charles is an old boy of Gordonstoun, one of the remotest schools in
the UK based in the northern Highlands, while Tony Blair, the leader of the
opposition, is a graduate of Fettes, an Edinburgh boarding school.
However, Scottish schools with the exception of Gordonstoun, are not
included in the FT-1,000 as they offer Scottish qualifications. Many offer
A-levels, but Gordonstoun is the only one to do so exclusively. It is ranked
386th, but the philosophy of its founders was ambitious and the school is
even less likely than most to accept judgment purely in terms of its
academic results.
The others offer more of a 'mixed economy' of A-levels and Scottish
qualifications, which are increasingly envied south of the border.
Proposals by the Headmaster's Conference  - which includes the top four
schools in the FT-1,000  - to reform the A-level structure to allow more
flexibility, and by the Committee of Vice-chancellors and Principals,
representing universities, to reform A-level syllabuses so that five
subjects become the norm, would both mean moving in the direction of the
Scottish system.
However, the mixed Scottish system defies adequate ranking. There is no
agreed conversion table between highers and A-levels  - although highers are
accepted at most English universities  - and different schools might
legitimately have different approaches.
Some take highers later because they need more time, others to take extra
subjects. For some the final year is irrelevant as they already have the
fifth-year highers needed to go to a Scottish university.
Therefore, the FT has made no attempt to rank them academically. Examination
of the proportions gaining A- and B-grades in highers does, however, suggest
that the big-city day schools tend to fare best.
Scotland has arguably the two most fiercely competitive markets for day
pupils in Britain, in Edinburgh and Glasgow. Both have several
well-established day schools fishing from a small pool of families able to
pay independent school fees. As the table shows, Dundee and Aberdeen also
have big independent day schools.
The boarding schools are more eclectic. Fettes, a Victorian-Gothic
construction near the centre of Edinburgh, has a strong high-church
tradition. Glenalmond  - with architecture designed to match Trinity
College, Cambridge  - was set up by Gladstone, the former prime minister,
and stands in dramatic open Perthshire countryside.
Despite the apparently remote locations, most of the boarding schools are
within easy reach of the bulk of the Scottish population.
In practice, most boarders tend to be either from Scotland or the North of
England, while there is also a pocket of 'expatriate Scots' from London.
Glenalmond is trying to encourage more English pupils by promoting the
advantages of the Scottish system  - which used to be regarded as a problem.
It says the flexibility will attract many, while the rigorous standards
needed for medicine degree courses might be easier to achieve if taken
gradually via highers.
+++++++ End of Leg 5 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
Scottish schools also offer a lot for those who want clean air and wide open
spaces, and the Duke of Edinburgh's award scheme is usually on offer.
Gordonstoun has a 150-acre estate, including over a mile of shoreline on the
Moray firth, while the big-city day schools also offer pupils outdoors
pursuits.
Kelvinside Academy, a Glasgow boys' school, has its own house in the
Cairngorms for skiing and hill-walking  - a valuable opportunity for
inner-city boys.
Fees for both boarding and day schools are in line with rates charged for
independent schools elsewhere in the UK. Last year's average boarding fee
per term was Pounds 3,259, compared with Pounds 3,261 for the nation as a
whole.
Day schools tend to be cheaper than in England, at Pounds 1,222 per term
(against an average of Pounds 1,262).
Full details of schools' performance in GCSEs and Standard grades, taken by
16-year-olds, and in Certificate of Sixth-Year Studies, are available from
the Scottish Council of Independent Schools. Scottish Council of Independent
Schools, Floor 2/1, 11 Castle Street, Edinburgh EH2. 031 220 2106.
</TEXT>
